        <div class="paragraph">
                <h3>Competitive Analysis</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="image-middle-container">
                <img src="/images/showcase/Competitive Analysis.png" width="100%" margin="40px 0">
        </div>
        <div class="paragraph">
            <p>
                    We can find that in the current SERP pages, <b>rarely updated basic information </b>almost always occupies half of the screen. However, do users really need these basic information? And do they need to view it every time ? </br>
                    What are the differences in information that celebrity fans need compared to people who don' t know stars? In order to answer these questions, I conducted a user interview and sorted out the answers.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="image-middle-container">
                <img src="/images/showcase/information.png" width="80%" margin="40px 0">
        </div>
        <div class="paragraph">
                <h3>User Study</h3>
                <p>
                    <b>Assumption</b></br>
                    The scenarios and expected information in SERP for different types of users (beginners, fans, and ordinary people) are quite different. 
                </br>
                </p>
                <div class="image-middle-container">
                        <img src="/images/showcase/User Study.png" width="100%" margin="40px 0">
                </div>
                <p>
                    <b> Ordinary people</b></br> 
                    "I prefer to read the news collection on wechat and I like reading everyone's comments. But I do sometimes earch for someone's videos."</br> 
                    <b>Beginners</b></br> 
                    "Generally when I watch TV shows and I find someone I feel I would like to know more about, I will use search engine to get more information."</br> 
                    <b>Fans</b></br> 
                    "I know every thing about the star, so I would only search for him when I need to verify something."
                </br> 
                </p>
            </br> 
                <div class="image-middle-container">
                        <img src="/images/showcase/baidu index.png" width="80%" margin="40px 0">
                </div>
            </br>
                <p>
                        According to Baidu Index, most people who search celebrities are fans or beginners who already know the basic info, and theiy expectied information are usually gossip news.
                </p>
                <div class="paragraph">
                    <h3>Findings</h3>
                    <p>
                            1. In the process from strangeness to familiarity, users expect different information from search engines.</br> 
                            2. Users often search for  celebrities with clear motivation and triggers
                                
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="paragraph">
                        <h3>Assumptions</h3>
                        <p>
                                1. Customize the SERP page for different users. Assigned different weights to related content based on how familiar the user is with the celebrity (and number of searches).</br> 
                                2. Create a framework that includes information that most users might need, and customize SERP page accordingly.</br> 
                                3. The SERP page plays the role of entrance and provides users with access to content of their interest.</br> 
                                4. Celebrity-related topics are very time-sensitive, so the weight and importance of infrequently changing information decline.</br> 
                                5. Different weights are assigned to related content based on how familiar the user is with someone.</br> 
                                6. Presents the information that the user wants most in the first page.
                                
                        </p>
                </div>
                <div class="paragraph">
                        <h3>Redesign</h3>
                        <p>
                                According to the previous analysis, I divided the contents of the SERP page into several parts in the form of notes representing different sorts of contents. When users search for celebtiries, these notes will be combined into corresponding personalized pages.
                        </br>
                        </p>
                        <img src="/images/showcase/pages.png" width="70%" margin="80px 40px">
                </div>
                <div class="paragraph">
                        <h3>Typical SERP Pages</h3>
                        <p>
                                According to user characteristics and needs, the types of modules that make up the SERP page and their relative areas are different.</br>
                                Here are the pages that may be assembled.
                        </p>
                </div>
